SUMMARY:21JPSI Speaker Series: "Japan's Caring Capitalism: Business Reinv
 ention and the Economic Importance of Guardrails" (Prof. Ulrike Schaede\,
  University of California - San Diego)
DESCRIPTION:This public event is open to all students\, faculty\, staff\,
  and members of the community. Please join us! Professor Schaede's prepar
 ed remarks will be followed by a discussion/audience Q&amp\;A.  &#160\;Ab
 out the talk:Japan's Caring Capitalism: Japan's business reinvention and 
 what a street racing manga teaches us about the economic importance of gu
 ardrails)  Japan's economy is much stronger than most people think. And i
 n these times of fast-changing technologies and rising geopolitical trans
 itions\, Japan's system of slower\, more balanced growth offers an attrac
 tive alternative to America's increasingly reckless capitalism. Yet\, sin
 ce the collapse of the bubble\, Japan has fallen into a cycle of negativi
 ty\, fueled by benchmarking Japan against what America considers a "good"
  company or economy. This pessimism has legitimated the introduction of A
 merican business practices\, almost without modifications. The resulting 
 financialization and short-termism are most visible in the rise of shareh
 older activism\, an innovation system focused on startups and generating 
 unicorns\, and increased job mobility.  To some extent\, American-style m
 arket discipline has helped Japan's ongoing business reinvention and the 
 shift from "Made in Japan" to "Japan Inside"\, i.e.\, a strategic pivot i
 nto upstream materials and components to become the technology anchor of 
 Northeast Asian supply chains. However\, Japan can do better than a na├»v
 e adoption of American business practices. Japan presents an alternative 
 system of capitalism that has guardrails against uncertainties and is mor
 e caring of society. This system entails different tradeoffs and cost-ben
 efit calculations\, and is anchored on more balance. These result in a di
 fferent type of strong economy\, with different processes of innovation.T
 his event is made possible thanks to generous financial support from the 
 Japan Foundation.About the speaker:Ulrike Schaede (Ńé”Ńā¬Ńé▒Ńā╗ŃéĘŃé¦Ńā╝Ń
 āć) is professor of Japanese business at the UC San Diego School of Globa
 l Policy and Strategy (GPS). She is the founding director of the Japan Fo
 rum for Innovation and Technology (http://jfit.ucsd.edu/) (JFIT)\, and th
 e faculty coordinator of the International Management track at GPS.      
                 Schaede's research focuses on Japanese business organizat
 ion\, strategy and management. Her main interest is to explore Japan's bu
 siness system and political economy\, with the goals to analyze different
  systems of capitalism and ways of organizing business\, and to identify 
 the social and economic efficiency consequences of these differences.    
                   Her 2020 book\, "The Business Reinvention of Japan: How
  to Make Sense of the New Japan and Why It Matters (https://www.sup.org/b
 ooks/title/?id=32247)" (Stanford University Press 2020)\, won the 2021 Ma
 sayoshi Ohira Memorial Prize from Japan\, as well as the 2021 U.S. Axiom 
 Business Book Award (silver medal\, "Economics"). In 2022\, it was publis
 hed in Japanese as ÕåŹĶłł THE KAISHA µŚźµ£¼Ńü«ŃāōŃéĖŃāŹŃé╣Ńā╗Ńā¬ŃéżŃā│ŃāÖ
 Ńā│ŃéĘŃā¦Ńā│ (https://www.amazon.co.jp/-/en/%E3%82%A6%E3%83%AA%E3%82%B1%E
 3%83%BB%E3%82%B7%E3%82%A7%E3%83%BC%E3%83%87/dp/4296113607/ref=tmm_hrd_swa
 tch_0?_encoding=UTF8&amp\;qid=&amp\;sr=) by Nikkei BP.                   
    In 2022\, Schaede also published a monograph titled "The Digital Trans
 formation and Japan's Political Economy (https://www.cambridge.org/core/e
 lements/abs/digital-transformation-and-japans-political-economy/282E0769C
 B887747A42369F4B78973C9)" (with Kay Shimizu)\, at Cambridge University Pr
 ess.                      She is also the author of "Choose and Focus: Ja
 panese Business Strategies for the 21st Century (https://www.amazon.com/C
 hoose-Focus-Japanese-Business-Strategies/dp/0801447062/ref=sr_1_1?dchild=
 1&amp\;keywords=schaede+choose+and+focus&amp\;qid=1632357699&amp\;sr=8-1)
 " (Cornell UP)\, and co-author of "Creating Ambidextrous Organizations: E
 xploration and Exploitation for Overcoming Inertia (https://www.amazon.co
 .jp/%E4%B8%A1%E5%88%A9%E3%81%8D%E3%81%AE%E7%B5%84%E7%B9%94%E3%82%92%E3%81
 %A4%E3%81%8F%E3%82%8B%E2%80%95%E2%80%95%E5%A4%A7%E4%BC%81%E6%A5%AD%E7%97%
 85%E3%82%92%E6%89%93%E7%A0%B4%E3%81%99%E3%82%8B%E3%80%8C%E6%94%BB%E3%82%8
 1%E3%81%A8%E5%AE%88%E3%82%8A%E3%81%AE%E7%B5%8C%E5%96%B6%E3%80%8D-%E5%8A%A
 0%E8%97%A4%E9%9B%85%E5%89%87/dp/4862762867/ref=sr_1_6?__mk_ja_JP=%E3%82%A
 B%E3%82%BF%E3%82%AB%E3%83%8A&amp\;dchild=1&amp\;keywords=schaede&amp\;qid
 =1595526565&amp\;sr=8-6)" (õĖĪÕł®ŃüŹŃü«ńĄäń╣öŃéÆŃüżŃüÅŃéŗ: Õż¦õ╝üµźŁńŚģŃé
 ÆµēōńĀ┤ŃüÖŃéŗµö╗ŃéüŃü©Õ«łŃéŖŃü«ńĄīÕ¢Č\, Eiji Shuppan 2020\, in Japanese).
  In addition\, she has published over 50 peer-reviewed articles\, book ch
 apters and company case studies. Her website\, www.thejapanologist.com (h
 ttp://www.thejapanologist.com/)\, features a blog on contemporary topics 
 in Japanese business\, society and political economy.                    
   At JFIT\, Schaede runs a weekly webinar series called JAPAN ZOOMINAR @ 
 UC SAN DIEGO (https://jfit.ucsd.edu/zoominar/index.html)\, where she disc
 usses contemporary Japan with global scholars\, business leaders and indu
 stry experts. In the classroom\, she teaches GPS's international manageme
 nt capstone class ("Strategy and Negotiation") and a management class tit
 led "Managing Business Reinvention in a Disrupted World." For the Japan F
 ocus of the MIA degree\, she has taught the required "Business and Manage
 ment in Japan\," as well as "Innovation and Entrepreneurship in Japan."  
         This event is made possible thanks to generous financial support 
 from the Japan Foundation.All 21JPSI events are 100% in-person unless oth
 erwise noted.          &#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  This public event is open to all studen
 ts\, faculty\, staff\, and members of the community. Please join us! Prof
 essor Schaede's prepared remarks will be followed by a discussion/audienc
 e Q&amp\;A.</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p><span style="text-decoration: underline
 \;"><strong>About the talk</strong>:</span><strong>Japan's Caring Capital
 ism: Japan's business reinvention and what a street racing manga teaches 
 us about the economic importance of guardrails)</strong></p><p>  Japan's 
 economy is much stronger than most people think. And in these times of fa
 st-changing technologies and rising geopolitical transitions\, Japan's sy
 stem of slower\, more balanced growth offers an attractive alternative to
  America's increasingly reckless capitalism. Yet\, since the collapse of 
 the bubble\, Japan has fallen into a cycle of negativity\, fueled by benc
 hmarking Japan against what America considers a "good" company or economy
 . This pessimism has legitimated the introduction of American business pr
 actices\, almost without modifications. The resulting financialization an
 d short-termism are most visible in the rise of shareholder activism\, an
  innovation system focused on startups and generating unicorns\, and incr
 eased job mobility.</p><p>  To some extent\, American-style market discip
 line has helped Japan's ongoing business reinvention and the shift from "
 Made in Japan" to "Japan Inside"\, i.e.\, a strategic pivot into upstream
  materials and components to become the technology anchor of Northeast As
 ian supply chains. However\, Japan can do better than a na├»ve adoption o
 f American business practices. Japan presents an alternative system of ca
 pitalism that has guardrails against uncertainties and is more caring of 
 society. This system entails different tradeoffs and cost-benefit calcula
 tions\, and is anchored on more balance. These result in a different type
  of strong economy\, with different processes of innovation.</p><p><em>Th
 is event is made possible thanks to generous financial support from the J
 apan Foundation.</em></p><div class="c-vertical-tabs" data-ms-component="
 vertical-tabs" data-vertical-tabs-display="vertical"><div class="c-vertic
 al-tabs__item" data-vertical-tabs-component="tab" data-vertical-tabs-stat
 e="is-open"><div class="c-vertical-tabs__content vertical-tabs__content-l
 ong open" data-vertical-tabs-component="content" aria-hidden="false" id="
 collapsible-1" role="region"><div class="s-wysiwyg"><div class="s-wysiwyg
 "></div><div class="s-wysiwyg"><strong><span style="text-decoration: unde
 rline\;">About the speaker:</span></strong></div><div class="s-wysiwyg"><
 /div><div class="s-wysiwyg"></div><div class="s-wysiwyg"><p><a href="http
 s://gps.ucsd.edu/faculty-directory/ulrike-schaede.html%C2%A0" target="_bl
 ank" rel="noopener"><strong>Ulrike Schaede</strong></a> (Ńé”Ńā¬Ńé▒Ńā╗ŃéĘŃ
 é¦Ńā╝Ńāć) is professor of Japanese business at the UC San Diego School of
  Global Policy and Strategy (GPS). She is the founding director of the <a
  href="http://jfit.ucsd.edu/">Japan Forum for Innovation and Technology</
 a> (JFIT)\, and the faculty coordinator of the International Management t
 rack at GPS.          </p><p>            Schaede's research focuses on Ja
 panese business organization\, strategy and management. Her main interest
  is to explore Japan's business system and political economy\, with the g
 oals to analyze different systems of capitalism and ways of organizing bu
 siness\, and to identify the social and economic efficiency consequences 
 of these differences.          </p><p>            Her 2020 book\, "<a hre
 f="https://www.sup.org/books/title/?id=32247">The Business Reinvention of
  Japan: How to Make Sense of the New Japan and Why It Matters</a>" (Stanf
 ord University Press 2020)\, won the 2021 Masayoshi Ohira Memorial Prize 
 from Japan\, as well as the 2021 U.S. Axiom Business Book Award (silver m
 edal\, "Economics"). In 2022\, it was published in Japanese as <a href="h
 ttps://www.amazon.co.jp/-/en/%E3%82%A6%E3%83%AA%E3%82%B1%E3%83%BB%E3%82%B
 7%E3%82%A7%E3%83%BC%E3%83%87/dp/4296113607/ref=tmm_hrd_swatch_0?_encoding
 =UTF8&amp\;qid=&amp\;sr=">ÕåŹĶłł THE KAISHA µŚźµ£¼Ńü«ŃāōŃéĖŃāŹŃé╣Ńā╗Ńā¬Ńé
 żŃā│ŃāÖŃā│ŃéĘŃā¦Ńā│</a> by Nikkei BP.          </p><p>            In 2022
 \, Schaede also published a monograph titled "<a href="https://www.cambri
 dge.org/core/elements/abs/digital-transformation-and-japans-political-eco
 nomy/282E0769CB887747A42369F4B78973C9">The Digital Transformation and Jap
 an's Political Economy</a>" (with Kay Shimizu)\, at Cambridge University 
 Press.          </p><p>            She is also the author of "<a href="ht
 tps://www.amazon.com/Choose-Focus-Japanese-Business-Strategies/dp/0801447
 062/ref=sr_1_1?dchild=1&amp\;keywords=schaede+choose+and+focus&amp\;qid=1
 632357699&amp\;sr=8-1">Choose and Focus: Japanese Business Strategies for
  the 21st Century</a>" (Cornell UP)\, and co-author of "<a href="https://
 www.amazon.co.jp/%E4%B8%A1%E5%88%A9%E3%81%8D%E3%81%AE%E7%B5%84%E7%B9%94%E
 3%82%92%E3%81%A4%E3%81%8F%E3%82%8B%E2%80%95%E2%80%95%E5%A4%A7%E4%BC%81%E6
 %A5%AD%E7%97%85%E3%82%92%E6%89%93%E7%A0%B4%E3%81%99%E3%82%8B%E3%80%8C%E6%
 94%BB%E3%82%81%E3%81%A8%E5%AE%88%E3%82%8A%E3%81%AE%E7%B5%8C%E5%96%B6%E3%8
 0%8D-%E5%8A%A0%E8%97%A4%E9%9B%85%E5%89%87/dp/4862762867/ref=sr_1_6?__mk_j
 a_JP=%E3%82%AB%E3%82%BF%E3%82%AB%E3%83%8A&amp\;dchild=1&amp\;keywords=sch
 aede&amp\;qid=1595526565&amp\;sr=8-6">Creating Ambidextrous Organizations
 : Exploration and Exploitation for Overcoming Inertia</a>" (õĖĪÕł®ŃüŹŃü«ń
 Ąäń╣öŃéÆŃüżŃüÅŃéŗ: Õż¦õ╝üµźŁńŚģŃéÆµēōńĀ┤ŃüÖŃéŗµö╗ŃéüŃü©Õ«łŃéŖŃü«ńĄīÕ¢Č\, 
 Eiji Shuppan 2020\, in Japanese). In addition\, she has published over 50
  peer-reviewed articles\, book chapters and company case studies. Her web
 site\, <a href="http://www.thejapanologist.com/">www.thejapanologist.com<
 /a>\, features a blog on contemporary topics in Japanese business\, socie
 ty and political economy.          </p><p>            At JFIT\, Schaede r
 uns a weekly webinar series called <a href="https://jfit.ucsd.edu/zoomina
 r/index.html">JAPAN ZOOMINAR @ UC SAN DIEGO</a>\, where she discusses con
 temporary Japan with global scholars\, business leaders and industry expe
 rts. In the classroom\, she teaches GPS's international management capsto
 ne class ("Strategy and Negotiation") and a management class titled "Mana
 ging Business Reinvention in a Disrupted World." For the Japan Focus of t
 he MIA degree\, she has taught the required "Business and Management in J
 apan\," as well as "Innovation and Entrepreneurship in Japan."          <
 /p></div><div class="s-wysiwyg"><em>This event is made possible thanks to
  generous financial support from the Japan Foundation.</em><em>All 21JPSI
  events are 100% in-person unless otherwise noted.</em></div><p>         
  &#160\;        </p></div></div></div></div>
